I"ö<h2 id="aim">Aim</h2>
<p>Interfacing of a 32k x 8 bit SRAM chip 62256 with ATmega32A microcontroller.
<!--more--></p>

<h2 id="project-description">Project Description</h2>
<p>A learning oriented project done to just ensure the correctness of the 62256 32k x 8 SRAM chips. It uses ATmega32A microcontroller burned with the â€œuC-SRAM-interfacing.cppâ€ using your AVR programmer, after compiling from avr8 gcc compiler.
<img src="/site/assets/images/blog/thumbnails/Interfacing 62256 SRAM using ATmega32A.png" alt="Resistor" width="auto" height="auto" /></p>

<p>Connect the pins of SRAM and uC as shown. Connect your uC to PC by UART-USB communication, he has used PL2303HXA for USB to UART Compile and run the â€œconsole-control-for-RAM.cppâ€ on your desktop/laptop computer. In the Console : â€œAdmin :â€ is where you type the input command. and â€œMicrocontroller :â€ is where the uC responds.
<img src="/site/assets/images/blog/Interfacing-SRAM/1.png" alt="Resistor" width="auto" height="auto" /></p>

<p>here on both the sides â€˜;â€™ is the string termination character.</p>

<p>to read the command is: â€œR-{address in RAM in decimal number};â€ (without quotes)</p>

<p>to write the command is: â€œW-{data to be written}-{address where you want to write data};â€ (without quotes)</p>

<p>Example : to read from address 11322; R-11322;</p>

<p>to write 112 to address 12136; W-112-12136;</p>

<p>Checkout whole code used in this tutorial at his GitHub repository <a href="https://github.com/RohanVDvivedi/Interfacing-62256-32Kx8bit-SRAM-using-ATmega32A">here</a></p>

